<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="254" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The British Minister of Supply</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Beaverbrook</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Presidents Special Assistant</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,
                                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-11">11 January,
                                        1942</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Harry</hi>: You asked me to make
                                arrangements to enable the United States Government to communicate
                                with colonies direct by Cable &amp; Wireless instead of through
                                London as at present.</p>
                            <p>That project has now been carried into effect for the duration of the
                                war according to your word.<note n="1" xml:id="d254fn1">In telegram
                                    No. 361 to London, January 30, 1942, not printed, Hopkins
                                    requested Beaverbrook’s further assistance with regard to
                                    establishing direct communications. Beaverbrook’s reply,
                                    transmitted in telegram No. 517 from London, February 4, not
                                    printed, described British measures taken and to be taken.
                                    (811.7441/44, 46)</note></p>
                            <p>I bless and praise thy matchless might,</p>
                            <p>Yours ever,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Max</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>